      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Valgrind can be a bit of a beast, especially on resource-constrained microcontrollers. In that case, you can try using a lightweight memory leak detection tool that's specifically designed for embedded systems. One popular option is Memcheck, which is a part of the GNU Debugger (GDB) suite. It's a bit like having a goblin in a small, portable box - it's compact and can be easily integrated into your code.\n\nAnother option is to use a custom memory leak detection tool, such as the one provided by the FreeRTOS operating system. This tool uses a simple, low-overhead approach to track memory allocation and deallocation, and can be easily integrated into your code. It's a bit like having a goblin that's always lurking in the background, watching for any suspicious activity.\n\nIf you're looking for something even more lightweight, you can try using a simple memory leak detection function, such as the one provided by the Newlib library. This function uses a simple, low-overhead approach to track memory allocation and deallocation, and can be easily integrated into your code. It's a bit like having a goblin that's always on the lookout for any memory leaks, but it's not as powerful as",
